ACINETOBACTER, DRUG RESISTANT - IRAQ (02)
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri, 18 Apr 2003 09:33:37 +0200
From: Silvio Pitlik <pitlik@post.tau.ac.il>

_Acinetobacter baumannii_ has became a major cause of
hospital-acquired infections in a growing number of countries,
including Israel. In my experience, this microorganism has a
combination of characteristics that makes it one of the sturdiest
nosocomial pathogens: 1) excellent environmental survival; 2)
extraordinary ability to become highly resistant to most or all
antibiotics except colistin; and 3) high virulence, with a
significantly greater case fatality ratio than other nosocomial
pathogens. Although initially seen in intensive care units
(neurosurgery, burns, and respiratory ICUs), it has recently spread
to general wards and nursing homes.
Its occurrence as a community-acquired pathogen has been reported
from limited areas in the world including Papua New Guinea and far
East Asia. The occurrence of _Acinetobacter spp_ infections amongst
wounded Iraqi natives is very intriguing and worrisome. Are those
community- or hospital-acquired infections? An urgent epidemiological
investigation should be carried out to answer this question. In
addition, stringent infection control measures should be applied in
order to contain the potential spread of this dangerous and virulent
pathogen.
--
Silvio Pitlik,MD
Director, Internal Medicine C and Infectious Diseases
Rabin Medical Center-Beilinson Campus
Petach Tikvah, Israel
<pitlik@post.tau.ac.il>
