Date: 18 Apr 2003
From: Larry Madoff <madoff@promedmail.org>
Several readers noted that imipenem is a carbapenem antimicrobial,
not a monobactam as stated in the original report. ProMED-mail
regrets the error and has corrected the archived report .
--
Larry Madoff, MD
Editor, ProMED-mail
<madoff@promedmail.org>
[As pointed out by Dr.Pitlik, community-acquired _Acinetobacter_
infections have been reported. As an example, Anstey and colleagues
reported 11 cases of bacteremic, community-acquired _A. baumanii_
pneumonias from the Northern Territory of Australia and reviewed 34
others (1). Cigarette smoking, alcoholism, chronic lung disease, and
diabetes were risk factors. The scenario has also been described in
Papua New Guinea (2) and other parts of Asia including Taiwan and
Malaysia, as well as more developed countries such as the USA (3) and
France (4).
More importantly, however, in regard to _Acinetobacter_ infections of
wartime injuries, Myron Tong reported that _Mimeae-Herellea_
(organisms of which some were renamed _Acinetobacter_) were the most
common Gram-negative bacilli isolated from wounds on day 1 of
hospitalization in the Vietnam conflict (5). Aarabi (6) found that
_Acinetobacter_ was the second most common cause of infection of
missile-related head wounds in a Iranian report from data collected
during the Iran-Iraq conflict.
Regarding _O. anthropi_, a bacterium formerly referred to as
Achromobacter CDC Group Vd, it is a Gram-negative, aerobic,
oxidase-positive and non-lactose fermenting organism for which most
reports in the medical literature are related to intravenous line
bacteremias (7).
1. Anstey NM, Currie BJ, Withnall KM: Community-acquired
Acinetobacter pneumonia in the Northern Territory of Australia. Clin
Infect Dis 1992;14:83-91.
2. Barnes DJ, Naraqi S, Igo JD: Community-acquired Acinetobacter
pneumonia in adults in Papua New Guinea. Rev Infect Dis
1988;10:636-39.
3. Bick JA, Semel JD: Fulminant community-acquired Acinetobacter
pneumonia in a healthy woman. Clin Infect Dis 1993;17:820-21.
4. Drault JN, Herbland A, Kaidomar S, et al: Community-acquired
Acinetobacter baumannii pneumonia. Ann Fran Anesth Reanim
2001;20:795-98.
5. Tong MJ: Septic complications of war wounds. JAMA 1972;219:1044-47.
6. Aarabi B: Comparative study of bacteriological contamination
between primary and secondary exploration of missile head wounds.
Neurosurgery 1987;20:610-19.
7. Jelveh N, Cunha BA: Ochrobactrum anthropi bacteremia. Heart Lung
1999;28:145-46. - Mod.LL]
